;; <=

;; **
;;; #### Try Empty
;;; 
;;; Suppose that instead of attempting to recover from a failure, we simply want to start over fresh. This would be similar to cleaning our entire kitchen if the pizzeria has one duplicate order (admittedly, a somewhat extreme response). We can use the `try-empty` as below. If a unit fails this results in an empty GRAPE being returned.
;; **

;; @@
(-> 
  (newgrape)
  (cheese-pizza 1000) ;; create a pizza with order 1000
  (try-empty (cheese-pizza 1000)) ;; should fail
  view)
;; @@
;; =>
;;; {"type":"list-like","open":"<span class='clj-lazy-seq'>(</span>","close":"<span class='clj-lazy-seq'>)</span>","separator":" ","items":[],"value":"()"}
;; <=

;; **
;;; #### Nesting Try-X Operators
;;; 
;;; Suppose we have a (rather demanding!) customer for our pizza shop who wants a pizza. If it's possible to add veggies they would like that, if they can't have veggies then they want pineapple, and if they can't have veggies or pineapply then they want only a cheese pizza.
;;; 
;;; First, let's create a new `pineapple-pizza` rule.
;; **

;; @@
(unit pineapple-pizza [oid]
      (prog (cheese-pizza oid) (add-topping oid "pineapple")))
;; @@
;; =>
;;; {"type":"html","content":"<span class='clj-var'>#&#x27;energized-valley/pineapple-pizza</span>","value":"#'energized-valley/pineapple-pizza"}
;; <=

;; **
;;; Now, let's write a graph program that satisfies the cutsomer's requests but also shows how we can test try-x operators inside of each other. On advantage of nesting is that it allows us to compose sophisticated failure handling mechanisms like `try-else-else-else...` and `try-else-skip` (as below). 
;; **

;; @@
(->
  (newgrape)
  (cheese-pizza 1000) ;; will succeed
  (try-else 
   (veggie-pizza 1000) ;; will fail
   (try-skip (pineapple-pizza 1000)) ;; will also fail
   ) 
  view)
;; @@
